When my brother in-law told me about this place and I looked at the menu, I was excited to go, but after a long day doing outdoor work at home, my wife and I just wanted to stay in for the night. My brother in-law asked if I would drop him off at Hooch and Hive, so I did, then I checked it out, went home to pick up my wife and came back.  I have worked the in the service industry for many years so I am biased for bartenders and others in the industry; my experience at Hooch and Hive was brief and was not good. After waiting for nearly 20 minutes for a drink, I approached a bartender who just got another patron a beer with a free beer ticket by politely stating, "Oh, I have a ticket too, could I put an order for mine as well?" and the reply I got was, "Did I look at you!?", a roll of the eyes and I instantly felt as if I were a plebeian.  Was I requesting a beer with a free ticket I received for being there? Yes. Would that beer be the last drink I ordered in the evening? Not at all, I preferred drinks off the menu and wanted to try other things on tap or a cocktail from their fresh ingredients; but first beer was the last and I didn't even finish it because I was disappointed with my experience.  After I received the reply I got, I stated that my wife and I were waiting there for 20 minutes and he argued that I was not, granted it was probably more like 15 minutes, but in all reality, that is unreasonable. What's even more unreasonable was after the bartender poured my beer and before he handed it to me, he proceeded to complain that I was receiving a free beer. I asked what he said and I stated that he wasn't being cool and that I get it because I also have bartended I in my life, but he ignored me.  I understand that I was not paying for my 'first' beer, but the experience of service was far from pleasant. After working in the industry for years, I fight for the people who serve and when my friends under tip, I do my best to educate the, (and I'm known for being an over tipper, sometimes 50-100%) so trust me when I say I care for those who work in the industry; but if a patron is trying to approach a bartender, a higher than thou reply is not well received because now I can never see myself in Hooch and Hive again and I would not recommend it to anyone. The one bartender who helped my wife with tea was friendly, but the bartenders seemed as if they were busy, but it didn't seem as busy as they were putting off. It just seemed as if they felt overwhelmed, but I'm on the outside looking in though I have experience doing the same thing.  If I were to receive a reply more along the lines of, "I'll be with you in on moment.", this review would be nonexistent or would read much differently; but it's obvious that the bartender I worked with didn't care for those he served.
